{"id":"2208.02929","submitter":"Cynthia J. Olson Reichhardt","authors":"C. Reichhardt and C.J.O. Reichhardt","title":"Nonlinear Dynamics, Avalanches and Noise for Driven Wigner Crystals","comments":"15 pages, 22 postscript figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.106.235417","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.mes-hall cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider the driven dynamics of Wigner crystals interacting with random\ndisorder. Using numerical simulations, we find a rich variety of transport\nphenomena as a function of charge density, drive, and pinning strength. For\nweak pinning, the system forms a defect free crystal that depins elastically.\nWhen the pinning is stronger, a pinned glass phase appears that depins into a\nfilamentary flow state, transitions at higher drives into a disordered flow\nphase, and finally forms a moving smectic. Within the filamentary flow phase,\nthe conduction curves can show switching dynamics as well as negative\ndifferential conductivity in which switching events cause some flow channels to\nbe blocked. The velocity noise in the filamentary flow regime exhibits narrow\nband characteristics due to the one-dimensional nature of the motion, while the\nmoving smectic has narrow band velocity noise with a washboard frequency. In\nthe disordered flow state, the noise power reaches a peak value and the noise\nhas a $1/f$ character. Our transport results are consistent with recent\nexperimental transport studies in systems where Wigner crystal states are\nbelieved to be occurring. Below the conduction threshold, we find that\navalanches with a power law size distribution appear when there are sudden\nlocal rearrangements of charges from one pinned configuration to another.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 4 Aug 2022 23:23:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-28"}
